      <exercise>
        <webwork seed="1">
          <setup>
            <var name="$g">
              <static>\begin{cases}x^2-5\amp x\lt5\\5x\amp x\geq5\end{cases}</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$a">
              <static>5</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$L[0]" category="number">
              <static>20</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$L[1]" category="number">
              <static>25</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$L[2]" category="number">
              <static>\text{DNE}</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$L[3]" category="number">
              <static>25</static>
            </var>
            <pg-code>
              $a=random(-2,10,1);
              $b=non_zero_random(-5,5,1);
              if($envir{problemSeed}==1){$a=5;$b=-5;};
              @f=(Formula("x^2+$b")->reduce,Formula("$a x")->reduce);
              Context("PiecewiseFunction");
              $g=PiecewiseFunction("x &lt; $a" => "$f[0]", "x >= $a" => "$f[1]");
              @L=($f[0]->eval(x=>$a),$f[1]->eval(x=>$a));
              $L[2]=($L[0]==$L[1])?$L[0]:Compute("DNE");
              $L[3]=$g->eval(x=>$a);
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p>Evaluate the given limits of the piecewise defined function.</p>

            <p><m>f(x) =<var name="$g" /></m></p>

            <p><ol cols="2" >
              <li><p><m>\lim\limits_{x\to <var name="$a" />^-} f(x)=</m><var name="$L[0]" width="10" /></p></li>
              <li><p><m>\lim\limits_{x\to <var name="$a" />^+} f(x)=</m><var name="$L[1]" width="10" /></p></li>
              <li><p><m>\lim\limits_{x\to <var name="$a" />} f(x)=</m><var name="$L[2]" width="10" /></p></li>
              <li><p><m>f(<var name="$a" />)=</m><var name="$L[3]" width="10" /></p></li>
            </ol></p>
          </statement>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <webwork seed="1">
          <setup>
            <var name="$f">
              <static>\frac{x^2-8.2x-7.2}{x^2+5.8x+4}</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$a">
              <static>-0.8</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$l" category="number">
              <static>-\frac{7}{3}</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabin[0]">
              <static>-0/9</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabin[1]">
              <static>-0.81</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabin[2]">
              <static>-0.801</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabin[3]">
              <static>-0.799</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabin[4]">
              <static>-0.79</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabin[5]">
              <static>-0.7</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabout[0]">
              <static>-2.41463</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabout[1]">
              <static>-2.34129</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabout[2]">
              <static>-2.33413</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabout[3]">
              <static>-2.33254</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabout[4]">
              <static>-2.32542</static>
            </var>
            <var name="$tabout[5]">
              <static>-2.25581</static>
            </var>
            <pg-code>
              do{$b=random(-1,1,2)*random(6,9,1);
              $c=non_zero_random(-5,5,1);
              }until($b!=$c);
              do{$a=non_zero_random(-5,5,0.1);}until($a!=$c);
              if ($envir{problemSeed}==1){$a=-0.8;$b=9;$c=-5};
              $f=Formula("(x^2-($a+$b)x+$a*$b)/(x^2-($a+$c)x+$a*$c)")->reduce;
              $l=Real(($a-$b)/($a-$c));
              @tabin=($a-0.1,$a-0.01,$a-0.001,$a+0.001,$a+0.01,$a+0.1);
              @tabout=map{$f->eval(x=>$_)} @tabin;
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p>Numerically approximate the following limits.</p>
            <p><ol>
              <li><p><m>\lim\limits_{x\to <var name="$a" />^{+}}\left(<var name="$f" />\right)=</m><var name="$l" width="10" /></p></li>
              <li><p><m>\lim\limits_{x\to <var name="$a" />^{-}}\left(<var name="$f" />\right)=</m><var name="$l" width="10" /></p></li>
            </ol></p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>For a numerical approximation, make a table:</p>

            <table>
              <tabular>
                <row bottom="medium">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$f" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabin[0]" />
                  </m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabout[0]" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabin[1]" />
                  </m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabout[1]" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabin[2]" />
                  </m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabout[2]" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabin[3]" />
                  </m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabout[3]" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabin[4]" />
                  </m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabout[4]" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabin[5]" />
                  </m></cell>
                  <cell><m>
                  <var name="$tabout[5]" />
                  </m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>

            <p>It appears that when <m>x</m> is close to <m><var name="$a" /></m> (whether slightly above or slightly below), that <m><var name="$f" /></m> is close to <m><var name="$l" /></m>. So
              <me>
                \lim_{x\to <var name="$a" />^{+}}\left(<var name="$f" />\right)=\lim_{x\to <var name="$a" />^{-}}\left(<var name="$f" />\right)=<var name="$l" />\text{.}
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>

